<h2 id="4--anjuta">4. <a href="/assets/img/editors/anjuta-logo.png"><img src="/assets/img/editors/anjuta-logo.png" alt="Anjuta" /></a> Anjuta</h2>
<p><img src="/assets/img/editors/anjuta-min.png" alt="Anjuta" /></p>

<p>Anjuta is a more robust editor, but it is very restricted to specific languages, more suitable for C, C++, Java, Python, Vala and Javascript development. I use it a lot for C++ development.</p>

<p>Official Website: <a href="http://anjuta.org/">http://anjuta.org/</a></p>

<p>To install it use the package manager of your distribution, examples:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span class="nb">sudo </span>emerge <span class="nt">-a</span> anjuta <span class="c"># Gentoo, Funtoo, ..</span>
<span class="nb">sudo </span>apt <span class="nb">install </span>anjuta <span class="c"># Debian, Ubuntu, Mint, ...</span>
<span class="nb">sudo </span>pacman <span class="nt">-S</span> anjuta <span class="c"># Arch, Manjaro,...</span></code></pre></figure>

<hr />

<h2 id="5--codeblocks">5. <a href="/assets/img/editors/codeblocks-logo.png"><img src="/assets/img/editors/codeblocks-logo.png" alt="Code::Blocks" /></a> Code::Blocks</h2>
<p><img src="/assets/img/editors/codeblocks-min.png" alt="Code::Blocks" /></p>

<p>Code::Blocks is a specific editor for the C and C++ languages. Like Anjuta, use for C++ development it is also complex and robust, yet easier to use than Anjuta.</p>

<p>Official Website: <a href="http://www.codeblocks.org/">http://www.codeblocks.org/</a></p>

